Right, let's dissect this rather comprehensive overview of Europe. You want it rewritten, expanded, and presented with a certain… *je ne sais quoi*. I can do that. Just don't expect me to hold your hand through it.

***

## Europe

This article delves into the vast and historically significant continent of Europe. For alternative interpretations or uses of the term, please refer to [Europe (disambiguation)](/Europe_(disambiguation)).

### Overview

Europe, a continent that sprawls across approximately 10,186,000 square kilometers (3,933,000 sq mi), holds the sixth-largest land area globally, accounting for a mere 2% of the Earth's total surface and a more substantial 6.8% of its landmass. It's a continent situated entirely in the [Northern Hemisphere](/Northern_Hemisphere) and, for the most part, in the [Eastern Hemisphere](/Eastern_Hemisphere). Its borders are defined by the frigid expanse of the [Arctic Ocean](/Arctic_Ocean) to the north, the vast [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) to the west, the sun-drenched [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea) to the south, and the immense landmass of [Asia](/Asia) to the east. The division between Europe and Asia is a matter of convention, generally following the [watershed](/Drainage_divide) of the [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains), the [Ural River](/Ural_(river)), the [Caspian Sea](/Caspian_Sea), the [Greater Caucasus](/Greater_Caucasus) mountain range, the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea), and the intricate network of the [Turkish straits](/Turkish_straits). This shared landmass with Asia forms the supercontinent of [Eurasia](/Eurasia), and with both [Africa](/Africa) and Asia, it constitutes [Afro-Eurasia](/Afro-Eurasia).

Politically, Europe is a mosaic of roughly [fifty sovereign states](/List_of_sovereign_states_and_dependent_territories_in_Europe), with an additional two to five states enjoying de facto independence but limited international recognition. [Russia](/Russia), the largest of these nations, commands a significant portion of the continent, covering 39% of its land area and housing 15% of its population, making it both the largest and most populous country within Europe. As of 2021, Europe's population stood at approximately 745 million, representing about 10% of the global population, placing it third after Asia and Africa in terms of sheer numbers. The continent's climate is remarkably temperate, largely influenced by the warming currents of the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream) originating from the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico). This oceanic influence moderates winters and summers, creating a milder climate than typically found at similar latitudes elsewhere. However, as one moves further inland, away from the moderating influence of the sea, more pronounced [continental climates](/Continental_climate) emerge, with greater seasonal variations.

The cultural tapestry of Europe is rich and multifaceted, weaving together distinct national and regional identities that collectively form the bedrock of much of [Western civilisation](/Western_culture). Its shared cultural roots are often traced back to the intellectual and artistic achievements of [ancient Greece](/Ancient_Greece) and the administrative and legal prowess of [ancient Rome](/Ancient_Rome), further shaped by their [Christian successors](/Christianity_in_Europe). The period following the [fall of the Western Roman Empire](/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire) in 476 CE saw the consolidation of [Christianization](/Christianization) across Europe during the [Migration Period](/Migration_Period), ushering in the [post-classical](/Post-classical) [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages). The [Italian Renaissance](/Italian_Renaissance), a period of profound artistic and intellectual rebirth, subsequently radiated across Western Europe, adapting to local traditions and fostering unique national expressions. This renewed focus on [humanist](/Renaissance_humanism) ideals, coupled with advancements in [art](/Renaissance_art) and [science](/Science_in_the_Renaissance), marked a significant transition into the modern era. From the [Age of Discovery](/Age_of_Discovery), spearheaded by maritime powers like [Spain](/Spanish_Empire) and [Portugal](/Portuguese_Empire), Europe exerted a dominant influence on global affairs, undertaking extensive explorations and establishing colonies across the Americas, Africa, Oceania, and Asia.

The [Age of Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment), the [French Revolution](/French_Revolution), and the tumultuous [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars) profoundly reshaped the continent's cultural, political, and economic landscape from the late 17th to the mid-19th century. The [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution), which ignited in [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain) in the late 18th century, catalyzed radical societal and economic transformations that rippled across Western Europe and eventually the globe. The two devastating [world wars](/World_war), both originating and largely fought within Europe, contributed to a decline in Western European global dominance by the mid-20th century, as the [United States](/United_States) and the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) emerged as superpowers, vying for ideological and geopolitical influence. The ensuing [Cold War](/Cold_War) physically and ideologically divided Europe along the [Iron Curtain](/Iron_Curtain), with the [North Atlantic Treaty Organization](/NATO) representing the West and the [Warsaw Pact](/Warsaw_Pact) the East. This division dissolved with the [Revolutions of 1989](/Revolutions_of_1989), the symbolic [fall of the Berlin Wall](/Fall_of_the_Berlin_Wall), and the eventual [dissolution of the Soviet Union](/Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union), paving the way for significant [European integration](/European_integration).

The process of European integration has been formalized through institutions like the [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe), founded in 1948, and most notably, the [European Union](/European_Union) (EU), which now encompasses the majority of the continent. The EU operates as a [supranational](/Supranational_union) political entity, existing somewhere between a [confederation](/Confederation) and a [federation](/Federation), built upon a foundation of [European treaties](/European_treaties). While its origins lie in Western Europe, the EU has undergone considerable [eastward expansion](/Enlargement_of_the_European_Union) since the collapse of the Soviet Union. A significant number of its member states have adopted a common currency, the [euro](/Euro), and participate in the [European single market](/European_single_market) and a [customs union](/European_Union_Customs_Union). Furthermore, the [Schengen Area](/Schengen_Area) has facilitated the abolition of internal border and immigration controls for many participating countries. The EU's democratic processes are robust, with popular elections held every five years, representing the second-largest democratic elections globally, surpassed only by those in [India](/Elections_in_India). Economically, the EU boasts the second-largest nominal GDP and the third-largest GDP by [Purchasing power parity](/Purchasing_power_parity) globally.

### Etymology

The name "Europe" itself is steeped in mythology and linguistic evolution. In classical [Greek mythology](/Greek_mythology), [Europa](/Europa_(consort_of_Zeus)) was a Phoenician princess, a figure central to the continent's naming. One prevailing etymological theory suggests her name derives from the Ancient Greek words εὐρύς ( *eurús* ), meaning 'wide, broad', and ὤψ ( *ōps* ), meaning 'eye, face, countenance'. Thus, Eurṓpē would translate to 'wide-gazing' or 'broad of aspect', an epithet possibly linked to the ancient concept of Earth itself as a wide-seeing entity in [Proto-Indo-European religion](/Proto-Indo-European_mythology). However, linguist [Robert Beekes](/Robert_S._P._Beekes) posits a pre-Indo-European origin for the name, arguing that a derivation from *eurus* would not logically yield the toponym Europa. Beekes points to related toponyms within ancient Greece, such as [Europos](/Europus_(Almopia)) in [ancient Macedonia](/Macedonia_(ancient_kingdom)).

Another perspective attempts to connect Eurṓpē to Semitic terms for 'west'. This theory posits a link to [Akkadian](/Akkadian_language) *erebu*, meaning 'to go down, set' (referring to the sun), or [Phoenician](/Phoenician_language) *'ereb*, signifying 'evening, west'. This Semitic root is also thought to be the origin of the Arabic *maghreb* and [Hebrew](/Hebrew_language) *ma'arav*. Nevertheless, [Martin Litchfield West](/Martin_Litchfield_West) has expressed skepticism regarding this connection, noting significant phonological discrepancies, and Beekes also considers a Semitic derivation improbable.

Across the globe, the name for the continent generally derives from Eurṓpē or Europa. In Chinese, for instance, the term is Ōuzhōu (歐洲/欧洲), an abbreviation of the transliterated Ōuluóbā zhōu (歐羅巴洲), where *zhōu* signifies "continent." A similar Chinese-derived term, Ōshū (欧州), is sometimes used in Japanese, particularly in the Japanese name for the European Union, Ōshū Rengō (欧州連合), though the katakana Yōroppa (ヨーロッパ) remains more common. In certain Turkic languages, the Persian term [Frangistan](/Frangistan), meaning "land of the [Franks](/Franks)," is colloquially used to refer to much of Europe, though official names like *Avrupa* or *Evropa* are also prevalent.

### Definition

The contemporary definition of Europe as a geographical entity has been in use since the mid-19th century. The continent is demarcated by significant bodies of water to its north, west, and south. Its eastern and northeastern boundaries are conventionally drawn along the [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains), the [Ural River](/Ural_(river)), and the [Caspian Sea](/Caspian_Sea). The southeastern boundary is typically defined by the [Caucasus Mountains](/Caucasus_Mountains), the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea), and the straits connecting it to the [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea).

**Definitions used for the boundary between Asia and Europe:**
*   **A:** [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains) - [Emba River](/Emba_(river)) - [Kuma–Manych Depression](/Kuma%E2%80%93Manych_Depression)
*   **B:** [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains) - [Ural River](/Ural_(river)) - [Kuma–Manych Depression](/Kuma%E2%80%93Manych_Depression)
*   **C:** [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains) - [Ural River](/Ural_(river)) - [Caucasus Mountains](/Caucasus_Mountains)

Islands are generally allocated to the nearest continental landmass. Thus, [Iceland](/Iceland) is considered part of Europe, while the nearby island of Greenland is typically assigned to [North America](/North_America), despite its political affiliation with Denmark. However, socio-political and cultural considerations occasionally create exceptions. Cyprus, while geographically closer to [Anatolia](/Anatolia) (Asia Minor), is politically aligned with Europe and is a member of the EU. Similarly, Malta, once considered part of [North-western Africa](/Maghreb), is now firmly classified as European. It's worth noting that in [British English](/British_English), the term "Europe" can sometimes exclusively refer to [Continental Europe](/Continental_Europe), excluding the British Isles.

The concept of a "continent" typically implies a large landmass largely encircled by water. Historically, the boundary between Europe and Asia has been a fluid concept, redefined multiple times since its earliest conceptualization in [classical antiquity](/Classical_antiquity). Early definitions relied on rivers, seas, and straits, without the inclusion of mountain ranges. Cartographer [Herman Moll](/Herman_Moll), in 1715, proposed a boundary formed by interconnected waterways leading to the Turkish straits, and further north, utilizing the [Irtysh River](/Irtysh_River) which flows into the [Ob River](/Ob_River) and ultimately the [Arctic Ocean](/Arctic_Ocean). The current eastern boundary, however, partially follows the Ural and Caucasus Mountains, a demarcation considered somewhat arbitrary and inconsistent with a strict definition of a "continent."

The division of [Eurasia](/Eurasia) into Europe and Asia largely reflects a spectrum of East-West cultural, linguistic, and ethnic differences rather than a sharp, definitive line. The geographical border between the two continents does not align with any state boundaries and is primarily defined by a few bodies of water. Countries like Turkey are considered [transcontinental](/List_of_transcontinental_countries), with their territory spanning both continents, divided by water. Russia and [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan) are similarly transcontinental, bisected by waterways. France, the Netherlands, Portugal, and Spain also exhibit transcontinental characteristics, with mainland territories in Europe and pockets of land in other continents separated by oceans. Spain, for example, possesses territories like [Ceuta](/Ceuta) and [Melilla](/Melilla) on the African continent, bordering Morocco. Under the current convention, Georgia and Azerbaijan are also classified as transcontinental, with mountains serving as the continental divide in their territories.

### History of the Concept

The initial recorded use of "Europe" as a geographical term appears in the [Homeric Hymn](/Homeric_Hymn) to [Delian Apollo](/Delian_Apollo), referencing the western coast of the [Aegean Sea](/Aegean_Sea). By the 6th century BCE, thinkers like [Anaximander](/Anaximander) and [Hecataeus](/Hecataeus_of_Miletus) began employing it to denote a part of the known world. Anaximander, and later [Herodotus](/Herodotus) in the 5th century BCE, placed the boundary between Asia and Europe along the Phasis River (modern [Rioni River](/Rioni_River)) in the Caucasus. Herodotus himself described the world as divided into three parts – Europe, Asia, and Libya (Africa) – with the [Nile](/Nile) and the Phasis rivers marking their respective boundaries. He also noted a differing opinion that the [River Don](/Don_River_(Russia)) served as the Europe-Asia divide. The geographer [Strabo](/Strabo), in the 1st century CE, established the River Don as Europe's eastern frontier. The [Book of Jubilees](/Jubilees) presented a biblical perspective, dividing the continents among the sons of [Noah](/Noah), with Europe extending from the [Pillars of Hercules](/Pillars_of_Hercules) at the [Strait of Gibraltar](/Strait_of_Gibraltar) to the Don River, separating it from Asia.

The convention that has persisted into modern usage was largely established during the [Roman era](/Roman_era) by authors such as [Posidonius](/Posidonius), [Strabo](/Strabo), and [Ptolemy](/Ptolemy), who identified the Tanais (modern Don River) as the boundary.

The Roman Empire, while influential, did not strongly emphasize continental divisions. However, following the disintegration of the [Western Roman Empire](/Western_Roman_Empire), the emerging [culture](/Western_culture) rooted in Latin and the Catholic Church began to associate itself with the concept of "Europe." The term "Europe" first appeared as a designation for a cultural sphere during the [Carolingian Renaissance](/Carolingian_Renaissance) of the 9th century. From this point, it increasingly signified the realm of influence of the [Western Church](/Western_Church), in contrast to both the [Eastern Orthodox](/Eastern_Orthodox) churches and the [Islamic world](/Islamic_world).

A cultural definition of Europe as the domain of [Latin Christendom](/Christendom) began to solidify in the 8th century. This concept emerged from the synthesis of Germanic traditions and Christian-Latin culture, defined in opposition to [Byzantium](/Byzantium) and [Islam](/Islam). Its geographical reach was initially limited to northern [Iberia](/Iberia), the British Isles, France, western Germany, the Alpine regions, and northern and central Italy. The enduring legacy of the [Carolingian Renaissance](/Carolingian_Renaissance) included this transition of "Europe" from a purely geographical term to one imbued with cultural significance. This shift influenced the perception of Europe's eastern borders, particularly in relation to areas under Byzantine, Ottoman, and Russian influence. The positive connotations associated with "Europe" by its users played a role in these evolving definitions. Notably, this cultural conceptualization was not applied to the Americas, which were viewed as distinct entities despite their colonization by European powers; instead, the concept of "Western civilisation" arose to encompass both Europe and its overseas colonies.

### Modern Definitions

The delineation of Europe's eastern boundary became a more pressing question in the Early Modern period as [Muscovy's](/Tsardom_of_Russia) expansion incorporated [North Asia](/North_Asia). Throughout the Middle Ages and into the 18th century, the traditional division of Eurasia followed Ptolemy, with the boundary tracing the [Turkish Straits](/Turkish_Straits), the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea), the [Kerch Strait](/Kerch_Strait), the [Sea of Azov](/Sea_of_Azov), and the [Don River](/Don_River_(Russia)) (ancient [Tanais](/Tanais)). However, maps from the 16th to 18th centuries varied in their continuation of this boundary beyond the Don's bend at [Kalach-na-Donu](/Kalach-na-Donu), into regions not detailed by ancient geographers.

Around 1715, [Herman Moll](/Herman_Moll) proposed a boundary following the northern course of the [Ob River](/Ob_River) and the [Irtysh River](/Irtysh_River), a major tributary of the Ob, connecting waterways from the Turkish Straits and the Don River all the way to the Arctic Ocean. His 1721 map presented this demarcation more clearly. However, Moll's reliance on rivers as boundaries was increasingly challenged by geographers who began to favor other criteria for continental divisions.

A significant departure from the classical Don boundary occurred in 1725 with [Philip Johan von Strahlenberg](/Philip_Johan_von_Strahlenberg). He proposed a new line along the [Volga River](/Volga_River), extending north to the [Samara Bend](/Samara_Bend), following the [Obshchy Syrt](/Obshchy_Syrt) (the [drainage divide](/Drainage_divide) between the Volga and [Ural Rivers](/Ural_River)), and then tracing the Ural River north to its source in the [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains). Strahlenberg was the first to suggest that mountain ranges could serve as continental boundaries, drawing the new boundary north along the Ural Mountains rather than the nearby rivers. This proposal gained traction within the Russian Empire and eventually became the commonly accepted convention, though not without its critics. [Voltaire](/Voltaire), in 1760, dismissively commented on Peter the Great's Europeanization efforts, suggesting that Russia, Scandinavia, northern Germany, and Poland were not entirely European. Geographers like [Halford Mackinder](/Halford_Mackinder) later questioned the validity of the Ural Mountains as a continental boundary.

Mapmakers continued to disagree on the boundary between the lower Don and Samara throughout the 19th century. The [Russian Academy of Sciences](/Russian_Academy_of_Sciences) atlas of 1745 depicted the boundary following the Don beyond Kalach towards [Arkhangelsk](/Arkhangelsk), while other mapmakers adhered to Strahlenberg's route. In the south, the [Kuma–Manych Depression](/Kuma%E2%80%93Manych_Depression) was identified around 1773 by naturalist [Peter Simon Pallas](/Peter_Simon_Pallas) as a valley that historically connected the Black Sea and the Caspian Sea, leading to its proposal as a natural boundary.

By the mid-19th century, three primary conventions for the boundary were recognized: one following the Don, the [Volga–Don Canal](/Volga%E2%80%93Don_Canal), and the Volga; another tracing the Kuma–Manych Depression to the Caspian Sea and then the Ural River; and a third abandoning the Don altogether, following the [Greater Caucasus watershed](/Greater_Caucasus_watershed) to the Caspian. The controversy persisted in geographical literature through the 1860s, with [Douglas Freshfield](/Douglas_Freshfield) advocating for the Caucasus crest as the "best possible" boundary.

Within Russia and the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union), the boundary along the Kuma–Manych Depression was widely adopted by 1906. In 1958, the Soviet Geographical Society formally recommended textbooks follow a boundary from [Baydaratskaya Bay](/Baydaratskaya_Bay) on the [Kara Sea](/Kara_Sea), along the eastern foothills of the Ural Mountains, then the [Ural River](/Ural_River) to the [Mugodzhar Hills](/Mugodzhar_Hills), and finally the [Emba River](/Emba_River), thereby placing the Caucasus entirely in Asia and the Urals entirely in Europe. The [Flora Europaea] adopted a boundary along the [Terek](/Terek_(river)) and [Kuban](/Kuban_(river)) rivers, south of the Kuma and Manych, but still with the Caucasus in Asia. Despite this, most Soviet geographers favored the Caucasus crest, a convention that became prevalent in the late 20th century, although the Kuma–Manych boundary continued to appear on some maps.

Some scholars view the division of [Eurasia](/Eurasia) into continents as a vestige of [Eurocentrism](/Eurocentrism), arguing that regions like China and India possess a diversity comparable to the entire European landmass, not just a single European country.

### History

#### Prehistory

The geological history of Europe spans millions of years, marked by the cyclical advance and retreat of continental ice sheets during the [Pleistocene](/Pleistocene) epoch, commonly referred to as [glacials](/Glacial_period) or periods of the [Quaternary glaciation](/Quaternary_glaciation). These cold phases, occurring at intervals of 40,000 to 100,000 years, were interspersed with shorter, more temperate [interglacials](/Interglacial) lasting approximately 10,000 to 15,000 years. The last glacial period concluded around 10,000 years ago, and Earth is currently in an interglacial period known as the [Holocene](/Holocene).

The earliest evidence of hominin presence in Europe comes from [Homo erectus georgicus](/Homo_erectus_georgicus), discovered in [Georgia](/Georgia_(country)) and dating back roughly 1.8 million years. Other hominin remains, approximately 1 million years old, have been unearthed in [Atapuerca](/Archaeological_Site_of_Atapuerca), [Spain](/Spain). [Neanderthal man](/Neanderthal_man), named after the [Neandertal valley](/Neandertal_(valley)) in [Germany](/Germany), appeared in Europe around 150,000 years ago, with fossil evidence placing them in present-day [Poland](/Poland) by 115,000 years ago. They eventually disappeared from the fossil record around 40,000 years ago, with their last known refuge in the Iberian Peninsula. Modern humans, or [Cro-Magnons](/Cro-Magnons), are believed to have arrived in Europe approximately 43,000 to 40,000 years ago. However, some archaeological findings suggest an earlier arrival of *Homo sapiens* in Europe around 54,000 years ago, predating previous estimates by a millennium. Early sites in Europe, dated to 48,000 years ago, include [Riparo Mochi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riparo_Mochi) in Italy, [Geissenklösterle](/Geissenkl%C3%B6sterle) in Germany, and [Isturitz](/Isturitz) in France.

The [European Neolithic](/European_Neolithic) period, characterized by the adoption of agriculture, animal husbandry, the development of settled communities, and the widespread use of pottery, began around 7000 BCE in [Greece](/Greece) and the [Balkans](/Balkans). This cultural shift likely stemmed from earlier farming practices in [Anatolia](/Anatolia) and the [Near East](/Near_East). The Neolithic culture spread from the Balkans along the [Danube](/Danube) and [Rhine](/Rhine) river valleys, associated with the [Linear Pottery culture](/Linear_Pottery_culture), and also along the [Mediterranean coast](/Mediterranean_coast) with the [Cardial Ware](/Cardial_Ware) culture. Between 4500 and 3000 BCE, these central European Neolithic cultures evolved further westward and northward, facilitating the transmission of new copper-working skills. Western European Neolithic sites are distinguished not by large agricultural settlements but by impressive field monuments, such as [causewayed enclosures](/Causewayed_enclosure), [burial mounds](/Burial_mound), and [megalithic tombs](/Megalithic_tomb). The [Corded Ware](/Corded_Ware) cultural horizon marked the transition from the Neolithic to the [Chalcolithic](/Chalcolithic) period. During this era, monumental megalithic structures, including the [Megalithic Temples of Malta](/Megalithic_Temples_of_Malta) and [Stonehenge](/Stonehenge), were constructed across Western and Southern Europe.

The modern indigenous populations of Europe trace their ancestry primarily to three distinct lineages: Mesolithic [hunter-gatherers](/Hunter-gatherer), who are descended from populations associated with the Paleolithic [Epigravettian](/Epigravettian) culture; Neolithic [Early European Farmers](/Early_European_Farmers) who migrated from Anatolia during the [Neolithic Revolution](/Neolithic_Revolution) approximately 9,000 years ago; and [Yamnaya](/Yamnaya_culture) [Steppe herders](/Western_Steppe_Herders) who expanded into Europe from the [Pontic–Caspian steppe](/Pontic%E2%80%93Caspian_steppe) of Ukraine and southern Russia around 5,000 years ago, coinciding with [Indo-European migrations](/Indo-European_migrations). The [European Bronze Age](/European_Bronze_Age) commenced around 3200 BCE in Greece with the flourishing of the [Minoan civilization](/Minoan_civilization) on [Crete](/Crete), which represented Europe's first advanced civilization. The Minoans were succeeded by the [Mycenaeans](/Mycenean_Greece), whose civilization collapsed abruptly around 1200 BCE, marking the onset of the [European Iron Age](/European_Iron_Age). Early [Iron Age Italy](/Iron_Age_Italy) and [Greece](/Archaic_Greece), from approximately the 8th century BCE, gradually gave rise to the historical period of Classical Antiquity, sometimes dated to 776 BCE, the year of the first [Ancient Olympic Games](/Ancient_Olympic_Games).

#### Classical Antiquity

Ancient Greece is widely regarded as the foundational culture of Western civilization, with its contributions to [democratic](/Democracy) principles and [rationalist](/Rationalism) thought often highlighted. The [polis](/Polis), or city-state, served as the fundamental political unit in classical Greece. In 508 BCE, [Cleisthenes](/Cleisthenes) established the world's first [democratic](/Athenian_democracy) system of governance in [Athens](/Athens). Greek political ideals experienced a resurgence in the late 18th century, influencing European philosophers and idealists. Beyond politics, Greece made significant cultural contributions in various fields: [philosophy](/Philosophy), [humanism](/Humanism), and [rationalism](/Rationalism) under luminaries such as [Aristotle](/Aristotle), [Socrates](/Socrates), and [Plato](/Plato); [history](/Historiography) with the foundational works of [Herodotus](/Herodotus) and [Thucydides](/Thucydides); dramatic and narrative verse, beginning with the epic poems of [Homer](/Homer); drama with playwrights like [Sophocles](/Sophocles) and [Euripides](/Euripides); medicine, advanced by figures such as [Hippocrates](/Hippocrates) and [Galen](/Galen); and scientific inquiry pioneered by [Pythagoras](/Pythagoras), [Euclid](/Euclid), and [Archimedes](/Archimedes). During the 5th century BCE, several Greek city-states successfully repelled the [Achaemenid Persian](/Achaemenid_Empire) incursions into Europe through the [Greco-Persian Wars](/Greco-Persian_Wars), an event considered pivotal in world history. The subsequent fifty years of peace, known as the [Golden Age of Athens](/Fifth-century_Athens), represented a seminal period in ancient Greece that laid many of the cornerstones of Western civilization.

Following Greece, [Rome](/Ancient_Rome) left an indelible mark on Western civilization, influencing [law](/Roman_law), [politics](/Politics), [language](/Latin), [engineering](/Roman_engineering), [architecture](/Roman_architecture), and [government](/Centralized_government). By 200 BCE, Rome had conquered [Italy](/Roman_Italy) and, over the subsequent two centuries, extended its dominion over [Greece](/Ancient_Greece), [Hispania](/Hispania) (encompassing modern [Spain](/Spain) and [Portugal](/Portugal)), the [North African](/North_Africa) coast, a significant portion of the [Middle East](/Middle_East), [Gaul](/Gaul) (modern [France](/France) and [Belgium](/Belgium)), and [Britannia](/Roman_Britain) (England and [Wales](/Wales)).

Expanding from its base in central Italy, the Roman Republic, beginning in the third century BCE, gradually consolidated its rule over the entire Mediterranean basin and Western Europe by the turn of the millennium. The Republic's end in 27 BCE marked the proclamation of the [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire) under [Augustus](/Augustus). The ensuing two centuries, known as the [Pax Romana](/Pax_romana), were characterized by an era of unprecedented peace, prosperity, and political stability across much of Europe. The empire continued its expansion under emperors such as [Antoninus Pius](/Antoninus_Pius) and [Marcus Aurelius](/Marcus_Aurelius), who spent considerable time on the Empire's northern frontiers engaged in conflicts with [Germanic](/Germanic_peoples), [Pictish](/Picts), and [Scottish](/Scottish_people) tribes. [Christianity](/Christianity) was legalized by Emperor [Constantine I](/Constantine_I) in 313 CE, following three centuries of intermittent [imperial persecution](/Persecution_of_early_Christians_in_the_Roman_Empire). Constantine also relocated the empire's capital from Rome to the city of [Byzantium](/Byzantium) (present-day [Istanbul](/Istanbul)), renaming it [Constantinople](/Constantinople) in his honor in 330 CE. Christianity became the sole official religion of the empire in 380 CE, and by 391–392 CE, Emperor [Theodosius I](/Theodosius_I) outlawed pagan practices. The end of antiquity is sometimes marked by these events, or alternatively by the [fall of the Western Roman Empire](/Fall_of_the_Western_Roman_Empire) in 476 CE, the closure of the pagan [Platonic Academy of Athens](/Platonic_Academy) in 529 CE, or the rise of Islam in the early 7th century CE. Throughout most of its existence, the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) remained a preeminent economic, cultural, and military power in Europe.

#### Early Middle Ages

The decline of the Roman Empire ushered in a prolonged period of transformation across Europe, often referred to as the "[Age of Migrations](/Age_of_Migrations)". This era witnessed numerous invasions and migrations by various tribes, including the [Ostrogoths](/Ostrogoths), [Visigoths](/Visigoths), [Goths](/Goths), [Vandals](/Vandals), [Huns](/Huns), [Franks](/Franks), [Angles](/Angles_(tribe)), [Saxons](/Saxons), [Slavs](/Slavs), [Avars](/Pannonian_Avars), [Bulgars](/Bulgars), [Vikings](/Vikings), [Pechenegs](/Pechenegs), [Cumans](/Cumans), and [Magyars](/Magyars). Renaissance thinkers like [Petrarch](/Petrarch) would later characterize this period as the "Dark Ages," a term that reflects a perceived decline in intellectual and cultural output compared to classical antiquity.

During this tumultuous period, isolated monastic communities served as crucial repositories for preserving and compiling accumulated knowledge from the classical era. However, written records from this time are scarce. Much of the literature, philosophy, mathematics, and other intellectual achievements of the classical period vanished from Western Europe, though they were diligently preserved in the east within the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire).

While the Western Roman Empire waned, Roman traditions and state structures persisted in the predominantly Greek-speaking [Eastern Roman Empire](/Eastern_Roman_Empire), also known as the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire). For much of its existence, the Byzantine Empire stood as the most powerful economic, cultural, and military force in Europe. Emperor [Justinian I](/Justinian_I) presided over Constantinople's initial golden age, establishing a comprehensive [legal code](/Code_of_Justinian) that continues to influence modern legal systems, funding the construction of the magnificent [Hagia Sophia](/Hagia_Sophia), and consolidating state control over the Christian church.

From the 7th century onwards, the protracted and frequent [Byzantine–Sasanian wars](/Byzantine%E2%80%93Sasanian_wars) significantly weakened both the Byzantine Empire and its neighboring [Sasanid Persian](/Sasanids) counterpart. This power vacuum allowed the Muslim Arabs to expand their influence into historically Roman territories, conquering the Levant and North Africa, and making inroads into [Asia Minor](/Asia_Minor). By the mid-7th century, following the [Muslim conquest of Persia](/Muslim_conquest_of_Persia), Islam penetrated the [Caucasus](/Caucasus) region. Over the subsequent centuries, Muslim forces extended their control to include [Cyprus](/Cyprus_in_the_Middle_Ages), [Malta](/Malta), [Crete](/Emirate_of_Crete), [Sicily](/Emirate_of_Sicily), and various parts of southern Italy. Between 711 and 720, most of the lands of the [Visigothic Kingdom](/Visigothic_Kingdom) in [Iberia](/Iberian_Peninsula) fell under Muslim rule, with the exception of small territories in the northwest, such as [Asturias](/Kingdom_of_Asturias), and largely [Basque](/Basque_people) regions in the [Pyrenees](/Pyrenees). This territory, known by its Arabic name [Al-Andalus](/Al-Andalus), became integrated into the expanding [Umayyad Caliphate](/Umayyad_Caliphate). The unsuccessful [second siege of Constantinople](/Siege_of_Constantinople_(717%E2%80%93718)) in 717 weakened the Umayyad dynasty and diminished its prestige. The Umayyads were subsequently defeated by the [Frankish](/Francia) leader [Charles Martel](/Charles_Martel) at the [Battle of Tours](/Battle_of_Tours) in 732, effectively halting their northward expansion. In the remote northwestern regions of Iberia and the central Pyrenees, Muslim influence was minimal. It was in these areas that the foundational kingdoms of [Asturias](/Kingdom_of_Asturias), [Leon](/Kingdom_of_Leon), and [Galicia](/Kingdom_of_Galicia) were established, initiating the eventual reconquest of the Iberian Peninsula. However, a coordinated effort to expel the [Moors](/Moors) was slow to materialize, as the Christian kingdoms were primarily preoccupied with internal power struggles. Consequently, the [Reconquista](/Reconquista) spanned nearly eight centuries, during which numerous rulers named Alfonso, Sancho, Ordoño, Ramiro, Fernando, and Bermudo contended with both Christian rivals and Muslim invaders.

The [Viking](/Viking) raids and the subsequent division of the Frankish Empire at the [Treaty of Verdun](/Treaty_of_Verdun) in 843 reshaped the political map of Europe. During the so-called Dark Ages, the [Western Roman Empire](/Western_Roman_Empire) fragmented under the dominion of various Germanic and Slav tribes, who established their territories across Western and Eastern Europe, respectively. The Frankish tribes eventually united under [Clovis I](/Clovis_I). [Charlemagne](/Charlemagne), a Frankish king of the [Carolingian](/Carolingian) dynasty who had conquered a vast swathe of Western Europe, was crowned "[Holy Roman Emperor](/Holy_Roman_Emperor)" by the Pope in 800. This event laid the groundwork for the establishment of the [Holy Roman Empire](/Holy_Roman_Empire) in 962, an entity that would eventually become centered in the German principalities of Central Europe.

[East Central Europe](/East_Central_Europe) witnessed the formation of the earliest Slavic states and the adoption of [Christianity](/Christianity) around 1000 CE. The powerful [West Slavic](/West_Slavs) state of [Great Moravia](/Great_Moravia) expanded its territory southward into the Balkans, reaching its zenith under [Svatopluk I](/Svatopluk_I_of_Moravia), which led to a series of conflicts with [East Francia](/East_Francia). Further south, the first [South Slavic states](/South_Slavs) emerged in the late 7th and 8th centuries, embracing [Christianity](/Christianity). These included the [First Bulgarian Empire](/First_Bulgarian_Empire), the [Serbian Principality](/Principality_of_Serbia_(early_medieval)) (which later evolved into the [Kingdom](/Kingdom_of_Serbia_(medieval)) and [Empire](/Serbian_Empire)), and the [Duchy of Croatia](/Duchy_of_Croatia) (which eventually became the [Kingdom of Croatia](/Kingdom_of_Croatia_(925%E2%80%931102))). To the east, [Kievan Rus'](/Kievan_Rus%27), originating from its capital in [Kiev](/Kiev), expanded to become the largest state in Europe by the 10th century. In 988, [Vladimir the Great](/Vladimir_the_Great) officially adopted [Orthodox Christianity](/Russian_Orthodox_Church) as the state religion. Further east, [Volga Bulgaria](/Volga_Bulgaria) established itself as an Islamic state in the 10th century but was eventually absorbed into Russia centuries later.

#### High and Late Middle Ages

The period spanning from approximately the year 1000 to 1250 is recognized as the [High Middle Ages](/High_Middle_Ages), followed by the [Late Middle Ages](/Late_Middle_Ages), which extended until around 1500. During the High Middle Ages, Europe experienced significant population growth, culminating in the [Renaissance of the 12th century](/Renaissance_of_the_12th_century). Economic expansion, coupled with a lack of security on overland trade routes, stimulated the development of crucial commercial networks along the coasts of the [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea) and the [Baltic Sea](/Baltic_Sea). The burgeoning wealth and increasing autonomy of certain coastal cities propelled the [Maritime Republics](/Maritime_Republics) to a prominent position on the European stage.

The mainland Middle Ages were largely dominated by the ecclesiastical and aristocratic social strata: the clergy and the nobility. [Feudalism](/Feudalism), which originated in [France](/France) during the Early Middle Ages, rapidly disseminated throughout Europe. In England, a power struggle between the nobility and the monarchy culminated in the drafting of [Magna Carta](/Magna_Carta) and the establishment of a [parliament](/Parliament). The Roman [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church) served as the primary source of cultural influence during this era, overseeing education across much of Europe through its monasteries and [cathedral schools](/Cathedral_school).

The Papacy reached its zenith of influence during the High Middle Ages. The [East-West Schism](/East-West_Schism) of 1054 irrevocably divided the former Roman Empire along religious lines, separating the [Eastern Orthodox Church](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church) in the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) from the Roman Catholic Church in the former Western Roman Empire. In 1095, [Pope Urban II](/Pope_Urban_II) initiated a series of [crusades](/Crusades) aimed at reclaiming [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem) and the [Holy Land](/Holy_Land) from [Muslim](/Muslim) control. Within Europe itself, the Church established the [Inquisition](/Inquisition) to combat heresy. In the [Iberian Peninsula](/Iberian_Peninsula), the [Reconquista](/Reconquista) concluded with the [fall of Granada in 1492](/Granada_War), marking the end of over seven centuries of Islamic rule in the southwestern peninsula.

In the East, a resurgent Byzantine Empire managed to recapture Crete and Cyprus from Muslim forces and reconquer territories in the Balkans. Constantinople, from the 9th to the 12th centuries, stood as the largest and most prosperous city in Europe, boasting a population of approximately 400,000. However, the Empire's strength was significantly diminished following its defeat at the [Battle of Manzikert](/Battle_of_Manzikert), and it suffered further weakening from the [sack of Constantinople in 1204](/Siege_of_Constantinople_(1204)) during the [Fourth Crusade](/Fourth_Crusade). Despite regaining Constantinople in 1261, [Byzantium](/Byzantine_Empire) ultimately fell in 1453 when [Constantinople was conquered](/Fall_of_Constantinople) by the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire).

The 11th and 12th centuries witnessed persistent incursions by nomadic [Turkic](/Turkic_peoples) tribes, such as the [Pechenegs](/Pechenegs) and the [Cuman-Kipchaks](/Cuman-Kipchak_Confederation). These movements triggered a substantial migration of [Slavic](/Slavic_peoples) populations towards the safer, densely forested regions of the north, temporarily impeding the eastward expansion of the Rus' state. Like many other regions across [Eurasia](/Eurasia), these territories were subsequently [overrun by the Mongols](/Mongol_invasion_of_Europe). The invaders, known as [Tatars](/Tatars), were predominantly Turkic-speaking peoples under Mongol suzerainty. They established the state of the [Golden Horde](/Golden_Horde), with its administrative center in Crimea, which later adopted Islam as its official religion and ruled over the territories of modern-day southern and central Russia for over three centuries. Following the disintegration of Mongol dominion, the first Romanian states, the principalities of [Moldavia](/Moldavia) and [Walachia](/Walachia), emerged in the 14th century. Prior to this, these regions had been successively controlled by the Pechenegs and Cumans. From the 12th to the 15th centuries, the [Grand Duchy of Moscow](/Grand_Duchy_of_Moscow) transformed from a minor principality under Mongol rule into the largest state in Europe. It successfully overthrew Mongol dominance in 1480 and subsequently evolved into the [Tsardom of Russia](/Tsardom_of_Russia), consolidated under the reigns of [Ivan III the Great](/Ivan_III_the_Great) and [Ivan the Terrible](/Ivan_the_Terrible), with steady territorial expansion eastward and southward over the following centuries.

The [Great Famine of 1315–1317](/Great_Famine_of_1315%E2%80%931317) marked the first major [crisis](/Crisis_of_the_Late_Middle_Ages) to afflict Europe in the Late Middle Ages. The period between 1348 and 1420 witnessed particularly severe population losses, with the population of [France](/France_in_the_Middle_Ages) being reduced by half. Medieval Britain endured 95 famines, while France experienced over 75 during the same period. Europe was devastated in the mid-14th century by the [Black Death](/Black_Death), one of history's most lethal [pandemics](/Pandemic), which claimed an estimated 25 million lives in Europe alone, representing one-third of the continent's population at the time.

The plague had a profound and destabilizing impact on Europe's social structure, fostering a "live for the moment" attitude, as vividly depicted by [Giovanni Boccaccio](/Giovanni_Boccaccio) in [The Decameron](/The_Decameron) (1353). It dealt a significant blow to the Roman Catholic Church's authority and led to increased [persecution of Jews](/Persecution_of_Jews), [beggars](/Beggars), and [lepers](/Leper). The plague recurred with varying intensity and mortality rates in subsequent generations until the 18th century, with over 100 documented plague [epidemics](/List_of_epidemics) sweeping across Europe during this period.

#### Early Modern Period

The Renaissance, a period of cultural transformation that originated in [Florence](/Florence) and subsequently spread throughout Europe, marked a significant shift. The emergence of a new [humanism](/Renaissance_humanism) was accompanied by the rediscovery of lost [classical Greek](/Classical_Greece) and Arabic knowledge, often preserved in [monastic](/Monastic) libraries and translated from Arabic into [Latin](/Latin_language). The Renaissance flourished across Europe between the 14th and 16th centuries, witnessing a remarkable flowering of [art](/Renaissance_art), [philosophy](/Philosophy), [music](/Music), and the [sciences](/History_of_science_in_the_Renaissance), supported by the patronage of royalty, nobility, the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church), and an emerging merchant class. Prominent patrons in Italy, including the influential [Medici](/Medici) family of Florentine bankers and the [popes](/Pope) in [Rome](/Rome), funded the prolific artistic output of *quattrocento* and *cinquecento* masters such as [Raphael](/Raphael), [Michelangelo](/Michelangelo), and [Leonardo da Vinci](/Leonardo_da_Vinci).

Political machinations within the Church in the mid-14th century led to the [Western Schism](/Western_Schism). For four decades, two rival popes, one based in [Avignon](/Avignon) and the other in Rome, claimed supreme authority over the Church. Although the schism was eventually resolved in 1417, the papacy's spiritual authority had been considerably undermined. The 15th century witnessed Europe's initial expansion beyond its geographical confines. Spain and Portugal, as leading naval powers, pioneered global exploration. These voyages reached the [Southern Hemisphere](/Southern_Hemisphere) in the Atlantic and the southern tip of Africa. [Christopher Columbus](/Christopher_Columbus) reached the [New World](/New_World) in 1492, and [Vasco da Gama](/Vasco_da_Gama) opened the maritime route to the East, connecting the Atlantic and [Indian Oceans](/Indian_Ocean) in 1498. The Portuguese explorer Ferdinand Magellan, leading a Spanish expedition, navigated westward across the Atlantic and [Pacific Oceans](/Pacific_Ocean) to reach Asia, culminating in the first [circumnavigation of the globe](/Timeline_of_Magellan%27s_circumnavigation), completed by Spaniard [Juan Sebastián Elcano](/Juan_Sebasti%C3%A1n_Elcano) between 1519 and 1522. Subsequently, Spain and Portugal established vast global empires in the [Americas](/Americas), Asia, Africa, and Oceania. France, the [Netherlands](/Netherlands), and England soon followed suit, building extensive colonial empires. In 1588, the [Spanish Armada](/Spanish_Armada) failed in its attempt to invade England. The following year, [England's unsuccessful invasion of Spain](/English_Armada) allowed [Philip II of Spain](/Philip_II_of_Spain) to maintain his naval dominance in Europe. However, two subsequent Spanish armadas met with failure in their attempts to invade England.

The [Habsburg dominions](/House_of_Habsburg) underwent significant partition in the centuries following the reign of [Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor](/Charles_V,_Holy_Roman_Emperor). The primary military logistical route for Philip II in Europe was the Spanish Road, which stretched from the Netherlands to the [Duchy of Milan](/Duchy_of_Milan).

The Church's authority was further eroded by the [Reformation](/Reformation), initiated in 1517 when German theologian [Martin Luther](/Martin_Luther) posted his [Ninety-five Theses](/Ninety-five_Theses), criticizing the practice of selling indulgences. Excommunicated in 1520 and condemned at the 1521 [Diet of Worms](/Diet_of_Worms), Luther's followers divided German principalities between [Protestant](/Protestant) and Catholic faiths. [Religious conflicts](/European_wars_of_religion) escalated across Europe as Protestantism spread. The plunder of the Americas financed Spain's centuries-long [religious persecution](/Spanish_Inquisition) within Europe. The [Thirty Years' War](/Thirty_Years%27_War) (1618–1648) devastated much of Germany, resulting in the deaths of 25% to 40% of its population and crippling the Holy Roman Empire. Following the [Peace of Westphalia](/Peace_of_Westphalia), France emerged as the dominant European power. The defeat of the [Ottoman Turks](/Ottoman_Empire) at the [Battle of Vienna](/Battle_of_Vienna) in 1683 marked a historic turning point, signifying the end of [Ottoman expansion into Europe](/Ottoman_wars_in_Europe).

Much of Central and Eastern Europe experienced a period of general decline throughout the 17th century, grappling with over 150 famines between 1501 and 1700. From the [Union of Krewo](/Union_of_Krewo) (1385), East-Central Europe was dominated by the [Kingdom of Poland](/Kingdom_of_Poland_(1385%E2%80%931569)) and the [Grand Duchy of Lithuania](/Grand_Duchy_of_Lithuania). The hegemony of the vast [Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth](/Polish%E2%80%93Lithuanian_Commonwealth) waned following the devastation wrought by the [Northern War of 1655–1660](/Northern_War_of_1655%E2%80%931660) (known as the [Swedish Deluge](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Deluge_(history))) and subsequent conflicts. The Commonwealth itself was eventually [partitioned](/Partitions_of_Poland) and ceased to exist by the end of the 18th century.

From the 15th to the 18th centuries, as the disintegrating khanates of the [Golden Horde](/Golden_Horde) were conquered by Russia, [Crimean Tatars](/Crimean_Tatars) from the [Crimean Khanate](/Crimean_Khanate) frequently conducted [slave raids](/Crimean%E2%80%93Nogai_slave_raids_in_Eastern_Europe) into Eastern Slavic lands, capturing numerous individuals for the slave trade. Further east, the [Nogai Horde](/Nogai_Horde) and [Kazakh Khanate](/Kazakh_Khanate) launched recurrent raids on Slavic-speaking territories of contemporary Russia and Ukraine for centuries, until the expansion and conquest of much of northern Eurasia by Russia.

The Renaissance and the rise of the [New Monarchs](/New_Monarchs) heralded the Age of Discovery, a period characterized by exploration, innovation, and scientific advancement. Key figures of the [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution) during the 16th and 17th centuries included [Copernicus](/Copernicus), [Kepler](/Kepler), [Galileo](/Galileo), and [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton). According to Peter Barrett, "It is widely accepted that 'modern science' arose in the Europe of the 17th century (towards the end of the Renaissance), introducing a new understanding of the natural world."

#### 18th and 19th Centuries

The [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War) brought an end to the "Old System" of alliances in Europe. Consequently, when the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War) escalated into a global conflict between 1778 and 1783, Britain found itself facing a formidable coalition of European powers without significant allies.

The Age of Enlightenment, an influential intellectual movement of the 18th century, championed reason and scientific inquiry. Discontent with the aristocracy and clergy's monopoly on political power in France culminated in the French Revolution, leading to the establishment of the [First Republic](/French_First_Republic) and the eventual downfall of the monarchy and much of the nobility during the initial [Reign of Terror](/Reign_of_Terror). [Napoleon](/Napoleon) Bonaparte rose to prominence in the aftermath of the French Revolution, establishing the [First French Empire](/First_French_Empire). During the [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars), this empire expanded to encompass vast territories across Europe before its ultimate collapse in 1815 at the [Battle of Waterloo](/Battle_of_Waterloo). Napoleonic rule facilitated the dissemination of French Revolution ideals, including the concept of the [nation-state](/Nation_state), and promoted the adoption of French models of [administration](/Centralised_government), [law](/Napoleonic_Code), and [education](/Education_in_France). The [Congress of Vienna](/Congress_of_Vienna), convened after Napoleon's defeat, established a new [balance of power](/Balance_of_power_(international_relations)) in Europe, centered around five major powers: the United Kingdom, France, [Prussia](/Prussia), [Austria](/Austrian_Empire), and Russia. This equilibrium persisted until the [Revolutions of 1848](/Revolutions_of_1848), which saw liberal uprisings sweep across Europe, with the notable exceptions of Russia and the United Kingdom. These revolutions were ultimately suppressed by conservative forces, resulting in few substantive reforms. The year 1859 witnessed the unification of Romania as a nation-state from smaller principalities. In 1867, the [Austro-Hungarian empire](/Austro-Hungarian_empire) was formed through the [Ausgleich](/Ausgleich), and 1871 saw the unification of both [Italy](/Italian_unification) and [Germany](/Unification_of_Germany) into nation-states from their constituent principalities.

In parallel, the [Eastern Question](/Eastern_Question) became increasingly complex following the Ottoman Empire's defeat in the [Russo-Turkish War (1768–1774)](/Russo-Turkish_War_(1768%E2%80%931774)). As the Ottoman Empire's decline appeared imminent, the Great Powers maneuvered to protect their strategic and commercial interests within its territories. The [Russian Empire](/Russian_Empire) stood to gain from this decline, while the [Habsburg Empire](/Habsburg_monarchy) and Great Britain favored the preservation of the Ottoman Empire. Concurrently, the [Serbian Revolution](/Serbian_Revolution) (1804) and the [Greek War of Independence](/Greek_War_of_Independence) (1821) signaled the beginning of the end of Ottoman rule in the [Balkans](/Balkans), a process finalized by the [Balkan Wars](/Balkan_Wars) of 1912–1913. The Congress of Berlin in 1878 formally recognized the de facto independent principalities of [Montenegro](/Montenegro), [Serbia](/Principality_of_Serbia), and [Romania](/Romania).

The [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution), which commenced in [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain) in the latter part of the 18th century, gradually spread throughout Europe. The introduction and adoption of new technologies spurred rapid urbanization, large-scale employment, and the emergence of a new working class. Subsequent reforms in social and economic spheres included the introduction of the [first child labor laws](/Factory_Acts), the legalization of [trade unions](/Trade_union), and the [abolition of slavery](/Abolitionism_in_the_United_Kingdom). In Britain, the [Public Health Act of 1875](/Public_Health_Act_of_1875) significantly improved urban living conditions. Europe's population surged from approximately 100 million in 1700 to 400 million by 1900. The Great Famine of Ireland, the last major famine recorded in Western Europe, resulted in widespread death and mass emigration. During the 19th century, an estimated 70 million people emigrated from Europe to various overseas colonies and to the United States. The industrial revolution also fueled substantial population growth, leading to Europe's share of the global population peaking at just over 25% around 1913.

#### 20th Century to the Present

The first half of the 20th century was dominated by two world wars and a severe economic depression. World War I, fought between 1914 and 1918, erupted following the assassination of [Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria](/Archduke_Franz_Ferdinand_of_Austria) by [Gavrilo Princip](/Gavrilo_Princip), a [Yugoslav nationalist](/Yugoslav_nationalism). Most European nations became embroiled in the conflict, pitting the [Entente Powers](/Entente_Powers) (including France, Belgium, Serbia, Portugal, Russia, the United Kingdom, and later Italy, Greece, Romania, and the United States) against the [Central Powers](/Central_Powers) (Austria-Hungary, Germany, Bulgaria, and the Ottoman Empire). The war resulted in over 16 million civilian and military fatalities, with more than 60 million European soldiers mobilized between 1914 and 1918.

The Russian Revolution plunged Russia into internal turmoil, overthrowing the [Tsarist monarchy](/Russian_Empire) and establishing the [communist](/Communist) [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union). This upheaval also led to the independence of numerous former [Russian governorates](/Governorate_(Russia)), including [Finland](/Finland), [Estonia](/Estonia), [Latvia](/Latvia), and [Lithuania], which emerged as new European nations. Austria-Hungary and the Ottoman Empire collapsed, fragmenting into separate states, and the borders of many other nations were redrawn. The [Treaty of Versailles](/Treaty_of_Versailles), which formally concluded World War I in 1919, imposed harsh sanctions on Germany, holding it solely responsible for the war. Excess deaths in Russia during World War I and the subsequent [Russian Civil War](/Russian_Civil_War), including the postwar famine, amounted to a combined total of 18 million. Under [Stalin's](/Stalin) leadership, grain confiscations by Soviet authorities contributed to a devastating famine in 1932–1933, causing millions of deaths. Surviving [kulaks](/Kulak) faced persecution, with many being sent to [Gulags](/Gulag) for forced labor. Stalin was also responsible for the [Great Purge](/Great_Purge) of 1937–38, during which the [NKVD](/NKVD) executed 681,692 individuals, and millions were subjected to deportation and exile to remote Soviet territories.

Serbian war efforts during World War I incurred immense human cost, with the country losing a quarter of its population. [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany), under the leadership of [Adolf Hitler](/Adolf_Hitler), initiated the devastating Second World War in Europe. Hitler is depicted here with his close ally, Italian dictator [Benito Mussolini](/Benito_Mussolini), in 1940.

The social upheavals that swept through Russia also influenced other European nations following the Great War. In 1919, the [Weimar Republic](/Weimar_Republic) was established in Germany, and the [First Austrian Republic](/First_Austrian_Republic) emerged. Italy saw the rise of [Mussolini's](/Benito_Mussolini) one-party [fascist](/Fascism) government in 1922, while [Atatürk](/Atat%C3%BCrk) established the [Turkish Republic](/Turkey), adopting the Western alphabet and state [secularism](/Secularism).

Economic instability, exacerbated by war debts and loans to Germany, created widespread hardship across Europe in the late 1920s and 1930s. This economic crisis, coupled with social unrest and the perceived threat of communism, fueled the growth of [fascist movements](/Fascism) throughout Europe, ultimately bringing [Adolf Hitler](/Adolf_Hitler) to power in [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany).

In 1933, Hitler assumed leadership of Germany and embarked on a mission to expand German territory. Germany reacquired the [Saarland](/Saarland) and the [Rhineland](/Rhineland) in 1935 and 1936, respectively. In 1938, [Austria](/Austria) was annexed by Germany following the [Anschluss](/Anschluss). The [Munich Agreement](/Munich_Agreement), signed by Germany, France, the United Kingdom, and Italy later that year, led to Germany's annexation of the [Sudetenland](/Sudetenland), a region of [Czechoslovakia](/Czechoslovakia) with a significant ethnic German population. In early 1939, Czechoslovakia was dissolved, with the [Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia](/Protectorate_of_Bohemia_and_Moravia) coming under German control and the [Slovak Republic](/Slovak_Republic_(1939%E2%80%931945)) being established. At this time, the United Kingdom and France pursued a policy of [appeasement](/Appeasement).

Amidst escalating tensions between Germany and [Poland](/Second_Polish_Republic) over the status of [Danzig](/Gda%C5%84sk), Germany signed the [Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact](/Molotov%E2%80%93Ribbentrop_Pact) with the Soviet Union, which included secret protocols allowing Soviet influence in the Baltic states and parts of Poland and Romania. Germany invaded Poland on September 1, 1939, prompting France and the United Kingdom to declare war on Germany on September 3, initiating the [European theatre of World War II](/European_theatre_of_World_War_II). The [Soviet invasion of Poland](/Soviet_invasion_of_Poland) commenced on September 17, leading to Poland's swift defeat. On September 24, the Soviet Union attacked the [Baltic countries](/Soviet_occupation_of_the_Baltic_states_(1940)) and, on November 30, launched an offensive against Finland, resulting in the costly [Winter War](/Winter_War) for the Red Army. British efforts to land troops at [Narvik](/Battles_of_Narvik) to aid Finland were aimed at encircling Germany and disrupting its access to Scandinavian resources. Concurrently, Germany deployed troops into Denmark. The period of relative inactivity known as the [Phoney War](/Phoney_War) persisted.

In May 1940, Germany launched an offensive against France through the Low Countries, leading to France's capitulation in June 1940. By August, Germany initiated a sustained air campaign against the United Kingdom, known as the [Battle of Britain](/Battle_of_Britain), but failed to force a British surrender. In 1941, Germany launched [Operation Barbarossa](/Operation_Barbarossa), invading the Soviet Union. On December 7, 1941, Japan's [attack on Pearl Harbor](/Attack_on_Pearl_Harbor) drew the United States into the global conflict as an ally of the [British Empire](/British_Empire) and other [Allied](/Allies_of_World_War_II) forces.

The "[Big Three](/Allies_of_World_War_II)" leaders – [Winston Churchill](/Winston_Churchill), [Franklin D. Roosevelt](/Franklin_D._Roosevelt), and [Joseph Stalin](/Joseph_Stalin) – are pictured at the [Yalta Conference](/Yalta_Conference) in 1945.

Following the decisive [Battle of Stalingrad](/Battle_of_Stalingrad) in 1943, the German offensive on the Eastern Front transitioned into a continuous retreat. The [Battle of Kursk](/Battle_of_Kursk), featuring the largest [tank battle](/Battle_of_Prokhorovka) in history, represented Germany's final major offensive on the [Eastern Front](/Eastern_Front_(World_War_II)). In June 1944, British and American forces landed in France during the [Normandy landings](/Normandy_landings), opening a crucial new front against Germany. Berlin ultimately fell in 1945 after the [Battle of Berlin](/Battle_of_Berlin), marking the end of World War II in Europe. The war was the largest and most destructive conflict in human history, causing approximately [60 million deaths worldwide](/World_War_II_casualties). Over 40 million individuals in Europe perished as a result of the Second World War, including an estimated 11 to 17 million who were victims of [the Holocaust](/The_Holocaust). The Soviet Union suffered immense losses, with around 27 million deaths (predominantly civilians), constituting about half of all global casualties in the war. By the war's conclusion, Europe faced a refugee crisis of over 40 million individuals. Post-war expulsions in Central and Eastern Europe displaced an additional 20 million people.

The two emergent [superpowers](/Superpower), the United States and the Soviet Union, became locked in a fifty-year [Cold War](/Cold_War), characterized by nuclear proliferation and geopolitical tension. Simultaneously, the process of [decolonisation](/Decolonisation), which had begun after World War I, gradually led to the independence of most European colonies in Asia and Africa.

The [Flag of Europe](/Flag_of_Europe), adopted by the [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe) in 1955, symbolizes the continent's aspiration for unity.

During the 1980s, [Mikhail Gorbachev's](/Mikhail_Gorbachev) reforms in the Soviet Union and the rise of the [Solidarity](/Solidarity_(Polish_trade_union)) movement in Poland weakened the rigid communist system. The opening of the [Iron Curtain](/Iron_Curtain) at the [Pan-European Picnic](/Pan-European_Picnic) initiated a peaceful cascade of events, leading to the collapse of the [Eastern Bloc](/Eastern_Bloc), the [Warsaw Pact](/Warsaw_Pact), and other communist states, thereby ending the Cold War. Germany was reunified following the symbolic [fall of the Berlin Wall](/Berlin_Wall) in 1989, and the geopolitical map of Central and Eastern Europe was redrawn once more. This period facilitated the resurgence of long-interrupted cultural and economic ties, placing previously isolated cities such as [Berlin](/Berlin), [Prague](/Prague), [Vienna](/Vienna), [Budapest](/Budapest), and [Trieste](/Trieste) back at the heart of Europe.

[European integration](/European_integration) also gained momentum following World War II. The [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe), founded in 1949 after a speech by Sir [Winston Churchill](/Winston_Churchill), aimed to foster European unity and achieve common objectives. It encompasses all European states except for [Belarus](/Belarus) and Russia. The [Treaty of Rome](/Treaty_of_Rome) in 1957 established the [European Economic Community](/European_Economic_Community) among six Western European nations, with the goal of a unified economic policy and a common market. In 1993, the EEC, the [European Coal and Steel Community](/European_Coal_and_Steel_Community), and [Euratom](/Euratom) merged to form the [European Community](/European_Community), which subsequently evolved into the [European Union](/European_Union). The EU established a [parliament](/European_Parliament), a [court](/European_Court_of_Justice), and a [central bank](/European_Central_Bank), and introduced the [euro](/Euro) as its common currency. Between 2004 and 2013, numerous Central European countries joined the EU, expanding its membership to 28 nations and re-establishing Europe as a significant global economic and political force. However, the United Kingdom withdrew from the EU on January 31, 2020, following a [referendum on EU membership](/2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum) held in June 2016. The ongoing [Russo-Ukrainian War](/Russo-Ukrainian_War), which began in 2014, escalated dramatically with Russia's full-scale invasion of [Ukraine](/Ukraine) on February 24, 2022, resulting in the largest humanitarian and refugee crisis in Europe since World War II, echoing the scale of the [Yugoslav Wars](/Yugoslav_Wars).

### Geography

Europe constitutes the western fifth of the [Eurasian](/Eurasia) landmass, distinguished by a higher ratio of coastline to landmass than any other continent or subcontinent. Its maritime borders are defined by the Arctic Ocean to the north, the Atlantic Ocean to the west, and the Mediterranean, Black, and Caspian Seas to the south.

The continent's topography exhibits considerable variation within relatively short distances. Southern regions are predominantly mountainous, with ranges such as the [Alps](/Alps), [Pyrenees](/Pyrenees), and [Carpathians](/Carpathians) descending northward through hilly uplands to the vast, low-lying northern plains, particularly extensive in the east. This expansive lowland region is known as the [Great European Plain](/Great_European_Plain), with the [North German Plain](/North_German_Plain) situated at its heart. A series of uplands also stretches along the northwestern seaboard, commencing in the western parts of Britain and Ireland and continuing along the mountainous, [fjord](/Fjord)-indented coastline of Norway.

This general description, however, simplifies a more complex reality. Subregions like the [Iberian Peninsula](/Iberian_Peninsula) and the [Italian Peninsula](/Italian_Peninsula) possess their own intricate geographical features, as does mainland Central Europe, with its numerous plateaus, river valleys, and basins that diverge from the broader trend. Islands such as [Iceland](/Iceland), Britain, and Ireland represent unique cases. Iceland, situated in the northern ocean, is considered part of Europe, while Greenland, though politically linked to Denmark, is geographically associated with North America.

The largest [European lakes](/List_of_largest_lakes_of_Europe) are concentrated in the northern part of the continent. The [Volga](/Volga) and [Danube](/Danube) rivers stand as the two longest [rivers of Europe](/List_of_rivers_of_Europe). Europe's most powerful [waterfall](/Waterfall) by [flow rate](/List_of_waterfalls_by_flow_rate) is the [Rhine Falls](/Rhine_Falls) on the [Rhine River](/Rhine).

### Climate

Europe is primarily situated within the temperate climate zone of the Northern Hemisphere, characterized by prevailing westerly winds. The continent's climate is notably milder than other regions at similar latitudes globally, largely due to the influence of the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream). This powerful ocean current transports warm water from the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) across the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) to Europe, earning it the nickname "Europe's central heating." The Gulf Stream not only warms the European coast but also heats the prevailing westerly winds that sweep across the continent.

This moderating effect is evident when comparing average temperatures. For instance, Aveiro, Portugal, experiences an average annual temperature of 16°C (61°F), while New York City, located at a similar latitude, averages only 13°C (55°F). Similarly, Berlin, Germany, lies at approximately the same latitude as Calgary, Canada, and Irkutsk, Russia. January temperatures in Berlin average about 8°C (14°F) warmer than in Calgary and nearly 22°C (40°F) warmer than in Irkutsk.

The significant influence of the [Mediterranean Sea](/Mediterranean_Sea) also plays a crucial role in regulating temperatures across Southern Europe, equalizing both annual and daily averages. The waters of the Mediterranean extend from the [Sahara desert](/Sahara_desert) northward to the Alpine arc in the northernmost reaches of the [Adriatic Sea](/Adriatic_Sea) near [Trieste](/Trieste).

Generally, Europe becomes progressively colder towards the north and from west to east. The climate is more oceanic in the west and transitions to a more continental character further east. This trend can be observed in the average temperatures recorded at locations situated along various latitudes, illustrating the diminishing influence of the Atlantic as one moves eastward.

#### Climate Change

[Climate change](/Climate_change) has demonstrably impacted Europe, with average yearly temperatures rising by approximately 2.3°C (4.14°F) since pre-industrial levels as of 2022. Europe is experiencing the fastest warming rate of any continent. International climate experts warn that global temperature increases must be limited to 2°C to avert the most severe [consequences of climate change](/Effects_of_climate_change); failure to significantly reduce [greenhouse gas emissions](/Greenhouse_gas_emissions) could see this threshold breached before 2050. The effects of climate change are widespread across Europe, varying in intensity and nature by region.

These effects include warmer weather patterns and an increased frequency and intensity of [extreme weather](/Extreme_weather) events, such as [heat waves](/Heat_wave), which pose significant [health risks](/Effects_of_climate_change_on_human_health) and impact ecosystems. While European countries are major contributors to global greenhouse gas emissions, the [European Union](/European_Union) and various national governments have implemented strategies for [climate change mitigation](/Climate_change_mitigation) and are pursuing an [energy transition](/Energy_transition), exemplified by initiatives such as the [European Green Deal](/European_Green_Deal).

### Geology

The geological history of Europe is a complex narrative stretching back billions of years, beginning with the formation of the ancient [Baltic Shield](/Baltic_Shield) (Fennoscandia) and the [Sarmatian Craton](/Sarmatian_craton) approximately 2.25 billion years ago. These, along with the [Volgo–Uralia](/Volgo%E2%80%93Uralia) shield, contributed to the formation of the [East European Craton](/East_European_craton), also known as [Baltica](/Baltica), which later became part of the supercontinent [Columbia](/Columbia_(supercontinent)). Around 1.1 billion years ago, Baltica and Arctica (as part of the [Laurentia](/Laurentia) block) coalesced into [Rodinia](/Rodinia), eventually re-splitting approximately 550 million years ago to reform as Baltica. Subsequently, around 440 million years ago, [Euramerica](/Euramerica) was formed from the union of Baltica and Laurentia, and further amalgamation with [Gondwana](/Gondwana) led to the creation of [Pangea](/Pangea). The subsequent breakup of Gondwana and [Laurasia](/Laurasia) approximately 190 million years ago, driven by the widening of the Atlantic Ocean, led to the eventual separation of Laurasia into Laurentia (North America) and the Eurasian continent. A land connection persisted between these two for an extended period via [Greenland], facilitating the exchange of animal species. Over the last 50 million years, fluctuating sea levels have significantly influenced Europe's shape and its connections with continents like Asia. The continent's current geographical configuration largely dates back to the [Late Tertiary](/Late_Tertiary) period, approximately five million years ago.

Europe's geology is exceptionally diverse and intricate, giving rise to the continent's varied landscapes, from the rugged [Scottish Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands) to the rolling [plains](/Plain) of Hungary. A key geological characteristic is the contrast between the mountainous terrain of [Southern Europe](/Southern_Europe) and the vast, partially submerged northern plain that stretches from Ireland in the west to the [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains) in the east. These two major topographical zones are separated by the Pyrenees and the Alpine-Carpathian mountain systems. The northern plains are further delineated in the west by the [Scandinavian Mountains](/Scandinavian_Mountains) and the mountainous regions of the British Isles. Significant shallow seas, including the [Celtic Sea](/Celtic_Sea), the [North Sea](/North_Sea), the [Baltic Sea](/Baltic_Sea) complex, and the [Barents Sea](/Barents_Sea), partially submerge sections of the northern plains.

The northern plain encompasses the ancient geological continent of [Baltica], and can thus be considered the "main continent" from a geological perspective. The peripheral highlands and mountainous areas in the south and west represent fragments derived from various other geological continents. Much of the older geology of western Europe was once part of the ancient [microcontinent](/Microcontinent) of [Avalonia].

### Flora

The flora of Europe has been profoundly shaped by millennia of human interaction and coexistence with agricultural communities. With the exception of [Fennoscandia](/Fennoscandia) and northern Russia, areas of pristine wilderness are now scarce in Europe, primarily confined to national parks.

The dominant natural vegetation cover across Europe is mixed [forest]. Favorable growth conditions prevail, with the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream) and [North Atlantic Drift](/North_Atlantic_Current) moderating temperatures in the north, and Southern Europe enjoying a warm yet mild climate, albeit with frequent summer droughts. Mountain ranges also exert a significant influence on vegetation patterns. East-west oriented ranges like the [Alps](/Alps) and [Pyrenees](/Pyrenees) channel moisture-laden winds inland, promoting forest growth. Conversely, north-south oriented ranges such as the [Scandinavian Mountains](/Scandinavian_Mountains), [Dinaric Alps](/Dinaric_Alps), [Carpathians](/Carpathian_Mountains), and [Apennines](/Apennine_Mountains) create rain shadow effects, resulting in well-forested windward slopes and considerably less favorable conditions on the leeward sides. Livestock grazing has impacted most of mainland Europe at some point, and the historical deforestation of natural forest habitats has disrupted original plant and animal ecosystems.

Floristic regions of Europe and neighboring areas, according to Wolfgang Frey and Rainer Lösch.

It is estimated that between 80% and 90% of Europe was once covered by forest, extending from the Mediterranean Sea to the Arctic Ocean. Despite the loss of over half of its original forests through centuries of [deforestation](/Deforestation), Europe still retains over a quarter of its land area under forest cover. This includes [broadleaf and mixed](/Temperate_broadleaf_and_mixed_forest) forests, the [taiga](/Taiga) of Scandinavia and Russia, mixed [rainforests](/Rainforest) in the Caucasus, and the [Cork Oak](/Cork_oak) forests of the western Mediterranean. While deforestation rates have slowed in recent times, and reforestation efforts are underway, vast areas have been replaced by monoculture [plantations](/Plantation) of [conifers](/Pinophyta), which grow more rapidly. These plantations, while extensive, offer diminished habitats for many European forest-dwelling species that require diverse tree species and varied forest structures. Natural forest cover in Western Europe is estimated at a mere 2-3%, while in Western Russia it is 5-10%. Iceland has the smallest percentage of forested area (1%), while Finland boasts the highest at 77%.

In temperate Europe, mixed forests comprising both [broadleaf](/Flowering_plant) and coniferous trees are predominant. Beech and oak are the most significant species in Central and Western Europe. In the north, the taiga is characterized by mixed spruce, [pine](/Pine), and [birch](/Birch) forests. Further north, within Russia and extreme northern Scandinavia, the taiga gives way to [tundra](/Tundra) as the Arctic region is approached. In the Mediterranean region, olive trees, well-adapted to the arid climate, have been extensively planted, alongside the widespread planting of [Mediterranean Cypress](/Cupressus_sempervirens) throughout Southern Europe. The semi-arid Mediterranean landscape features considerable scrub forest. A narrow east-west band of Eurasian [grassland](/Grassland), known as the [steppe](/Steppe), extends westward from [Ukraine](/Ukraine) and southern Russia, terminating in Hungary and transitioning into taiga to the north.

### Fauna

The distribution of [European fauna](/Fauna_of_Europe) has been significantly influenced by glacial cycles during the [most recent ice age](/Quaternary_glaciation) and the long-term presence and impact of humans. Across much of Europe, large animal species and top [predator](/Predator) populations have been severely depleted due to hunting. The [woolly mammoth](/Woolly_mammoth), for instance, became extinct before the close of the [Neolithic](/Neolithic) period. Today, species such as [wolves](/Wolf) (carnivores) and [bears](/Bear) (omnivores), once widespread, are endangered. Their habitats have progressively shrunk, forcing them into increasingly remote areas. The [European brown bear](/European_brown_bear) is now primarily found in the Balkan Peninsula, Scandinavia, and Russia, with smaller, fragmented populations persisting in other parts of Europe, such as the Alps and Pyrenees, where their habitats are severely threatened. [Polar bears](/Polar_bear) can be observed on [Svalbard](/Svalbard), a Norwegian archipelago situated far north of Scandinavia. The [Eurasian wolf](/Eurasian_wolf), Europe's second-largest predator after the brown bear, is predominantly found in Central and Eastern Europe and the Balkans, with limited packs also present in pockets of [Western Europe](/Western_Europe).

Once roaming the vast temperate forests of Eurasia, [European bison](/European_bison) now survive in nature preserves, most notably in [Białowieża Forest](/Bia%C5%82owie%C5%BCa_Forest) on the border between [Poland](/Poland) and [Belarus](/Belarus).

Other significant carnivores in Europe include the [European wildcat](/European_wildcat), [red fox](/Red_fox), [arctic fox](/Arctic_fox), [golden jackal](/Golden_jackal), various species of [martens](/Marten), the [European hedgehog](/European_hedgehog), a range of reptiles (including vipers and grass snakes) and amphibians, as well as numerous bird species, such as [owls](/Owl), [hawks](/Hawk), and other birds of prey.

Herbivorous fauna in Europe is diverse, encompassing snails, larvae, fish, various bird species, and mammals like rodents, deer, [roe deer](/Roe_deer), and wild boars. Mountainous regions are home to animals such as [marmots](/Marmots), [steinbocks](/Steinbocks), and [chamois](/Chamois). Insect species, including the [small tortoiseshell](/Small_tortoiseshell) butterfly, contribute to the continent's biodiversity.

Marine life also forms an integral part of Europe's fauna. Phytoplankton constitutes the primary component of marine flora, while zooplankton, [molluscs](/Mollusc), [echinoderms](/Echinoderm), various [crustaceans](/Crustacean), [squids](/Squid), [octopuses](/Octopuses), fish, [dolphins](/Dolphin), and [whales](/Whales) inhabit European seas.

Biodiversity conservation in Europe is facilitated by the Council of Europe's [Bern Convention](/Convention_on_the_Conservation_of_European_Wildlife_and_Natural_Habitats), which has also been ratified by the [European Community](/European_Community) and several non-European states.

### Politics

The political landscape of Europe is largely a product of the reorganizations that followed the [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars) in 1815. The predominant form of government across Europe today is [parliamentary democracy](/Parliamentary_democracy), most commonly structured as a [republic]. In 1815, monarchies were the prevailing form of government, whereas Europe's current eleven monarchies are all [constitutional](/Constitutional_monarchy).

[European integration](/European_integration) represents the ongoing process of political, legal, economic, and, in some instances, social and cultural unification of European states, a movement actively promoted by the sponsoring powers of the [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe) since the conclusion of [World War II](/Second_World_War). The [European Union](/European_Union) has emerged as the central institution for economic integration on the continent since its establishment in 1993. More recently, the [Eurasian Economic Union](/Eurasian_Economic_Union) has been formed as a counterpart, comprising several former Soviet states.

Currently, 27 European states are members of the politico-economic European Union, 26 participate in the border-free [Schengen Area](/Schengen_Area), and 20 utilize the [Eurozone](/Eurozone) currency. Other significant European organizations include the [Nordic Council](/Nordic_Council), [Benelux](/Benelux), the [Baltic Assembly](/Baltic_Assembly), and the [Visegrád Group](/Visegr%C3%A1d_Group).

According to the [V-Dem Democracy indices](/V-Dem_Democracy_indices) for 2024, the least democratic countries in Europe are [Belarus](/Belarus), Russia, and [Turkey](/Turkey).

